Results: gmd:identificationInfo.gmd:MD_DataIdentification.gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString.#text:§The main objectives of the project are to 1) identify the geographical origin(s) of poppy including the location(s) of its wild progenitor(s) and of its domestication, 2) define a chrono-cultural framework for its early domestication process and dispersal from Prehistory to the end of the Iron Age (6000-50 cal BC). Using archaeological material, as well as sampling of modern biodiversity kept in seed banks, this pioneering project involves several disciplines – archaeobotany, dating techniques, genomics, geometric morphometric methods, spatial analysis – to elucidate the role of the opium poppy in Europe’s natural and cultural heritage. The project is financed by the Fondation Fyssen (2018), the ANR (ANR-21-CE27-0006, 2022-2025) and the FCT (PTDC/HAR-ARQ/1709/2021, 2022-2024).

Results: gmd:dataQualityInfo.gmd:DQ_DataQuality.gmd:lineage.gmd:LI_Lineage.gmd:statement.gco:CharacterString.#text:§The archaeological database integrate an exhaustive review of archaeological records of opium poppy to make a spatial analysis of its early dispersal between 6000 and 50 BCE. This database is based the inventory initiated during the Fyssen project for the Early Neolithic period, The DNA data includes modern accessions of cultivated poppy as well as modern P. somniferum subsp. setigerum accessions selected from public seed banks (ARS-GRIN in the US, IPK in Germany, CRF in Spain, Nordgen in Sweden). For each accession, a part of the seeds will be kept for geometric-morphometrics (GMM). In addition, accessions of others modern wild Papaver species from South-West Asia and the Mediterranea. In addition, samples from herbarium specimens kept in several European herbaria (e.g. Paris, Geneva) from worldwide wild and cultivated opium poppy are processed as ancient DNA (aDNA). GMM data includes several seeds from accessions of wild ( P. somniferum subsp. setigerum), cultivated opium poppy (P. somniferum subsp. somniferum) and other modern species are selected among the accessions analysed by DNA.
